<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,981,727,790]" box="[151,981,727,754]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,981,727,754]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,981,727,754]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
Key to species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1821" box="[492,611,727,754]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,611,727,754]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Dendarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[687,742,727,753]" name="Iran" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Iran</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[804,981,727,753]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,981,727,790]" box="[151,708,763,790]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">(on males = strongly widened protarsomeres 1–4)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
1 Posterior angles of pronotum acute, strongly protruding to humeral region of elytra (
<figureCitation box="[1043,1122,832,854]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Strial punctures large, strongly elongate, sparse, located each in very deep wide impression; interstriae slightly convex (
<figureCitation box="[1071,1148,861,884]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Mesotarsi strongly widened, mesotarsomeres 2 and 3 weakly transverse; mesotarsomeres 1–3 with full hair brush on sole (
<figureCitation box="[1123,1196,891,913]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
)....... 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Menetries" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[1306,1436,891,912]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crenulatus">
<emphasis box="[1306,1436,891,912]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. crenulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Posterior angles of pronotum from obtuse to right-angled, sometimes weakly protruding, but not deeply inserted to humeral region of elytra (
<figureCitation box="[391,472,949,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[484,543,950,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@6.[151,1436,181,1771]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dendarus leonhardi. A = lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = lectotype, male, laterally; E = male (non-type), dorsally; F = female (non-type), dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669251/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">3A, E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[554,586,949,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1028,1052]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,170,1012]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1436,166,1012]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Dendarus spp., male, head and pronotum. A = D. matthewsi; B = D. simplex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669261/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">5A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[597,628,949,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669265/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">6A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[640,672,950,972]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1941,1965]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,1022,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-378@11.[151,1436,1016,1917]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Dendarus vagabundus, male, holotype of D. vagans (junior homonym). A = habitus, laterally; B = habitus, dorsally; C = abdomen; D = dissected aedeagus and tergite VII; E = labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669267/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">7A</figureCitation>
). Strial punctures small or moderate in size, round (
<figureCitation box="[1181,1262,949,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,272,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-66@3.[151,1436,270,1664]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dendarus armeniacus, type specimens. A = Lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = type series; E = male mesotibia, ventrally; F = male mesotibia, laterally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669243/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1274,1305,950,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1317,1348,950,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669255/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">4A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1359,1391,949,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669265/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">6A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1402,1432,950,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1941,1965]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,1022,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-378@11.[151,1436,1016,1917]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Dendarus vagabundus, male, holotype of D. vagans (junior homonym). A = habitus, laterally; B = habitus, dorsally; C = abdomen; D = dissected aedeagus and tergite VII; E = labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669267/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">7B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[226,287,979,1000]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669271/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">8A, D</figureCitation>
), sometimes comparatively strongly impressed, but in this case very sparse (19–22 punctures in one row) (
<figureCitation box="[1316,1425,979,1001]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@6.[151,1436,181,1771]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dendarus leonhardi. A = lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = lectotype, male, laterally; E = male (non-type), dorsally; F = female (non-type), dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669251/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 3A, E</figureCitation>
); interstriae flattened. Mesotarsi narrow or slightly widened, mesotarsomeres longitudinal; only mesotarsomeres 2 and 3 can be with full brush or reduced tuft (
<figureCitation box="[527,628,1037,1059]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,272,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-66@3.[151,1436,270,1664]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dendarus armeniacus, type specimens. A = Lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = type series; E = male mesotibia, ventrally; F = male mesotibia, laterally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669243/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 1E, F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[638,668,1038,1059]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">2B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[678,708,1038,1059]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669255/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">4B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[718,748,1037,1059]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669265/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">6B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[758,786,1038,1060]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669271/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">8B</figureCitation>
)................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
2 Body completely matt. Elytral striae with sparse deeply impressed 19–22 round punctures in each row (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1356,1067,1089]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@6.[151,1436,181,1771]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dendarus leonhardi. A = lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = lectotype, male, laterally; E = male (non-type), dorsally; F = female (non-type), dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669251/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 3A, D, E</figureCitation>
).............................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schuster" authorityYear="1940" box="[1314,1436,1096,1118]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonhardi">
<emphasis box="[1314,1436,1096,1118]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. leonhardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Body more or less shiny. Elytral striae with not impressed or weakly impressed 27–30 round small punctures in each row (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[267,299,1155,1176]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669255/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">4A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[309,340,1155,1177]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669265/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">6A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[350,380,1155,1176]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1941,1965]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,1022,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-378@11.[151,1436,1016,1917]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Dendarus vagabundus, male, holotype of D. vagans (junior homonym). A = habitus, laterally; B = habitus, dorsally; C = abdomen; D = dissected aedeagus and tergite VII; E = labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669267/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">7B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[390,449,1155,1176]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669271/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">8A, D</figureCitation>
)................................................................................ 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
3 Pronotum and head shiny, and elytra matt (
<figureCitation box="[641,719,1184,1206]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669265/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
). Puncturation of pronotum uneven: fine and sparse, with round punctures at middle and sharply coarse and dense, elongate, often merged punctures on lateral sides (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1172,1213,1235]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669265/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
)...... 
<taxonomicName box="[1275,1436,1214,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transcaspicus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1436,1214,1235]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. transcaspicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Dorsal side uniformly, strongly, moderately or weakly shiny (
<figureCitation box="[834,915,1243,1265]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,272,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-66@3.[151,1436,270,1664]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dendarus armeniacus, type specimens. A = Lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = type series; E = male mesotibia, ventrally; F = male mesotibia, laterally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669243/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[928,959,1243,1264]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[972,1003,1243,1264]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669255/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">4A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1015,1079,1243,1264]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669271/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">8A, D</figureCitation>
). Puncturation of pronotum uniform (dense or sparse), with round punctures................................................................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" box="[151,1436,1301,1323]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1301,1323]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
4 Protibiae narrow, 4.3 times as long as wide (at widest level) (
<figureCitation box="[812,888,1301,1323]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,932,956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,908]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Dendarus spp., male protibia. A = D. armeniacus; B = D. crenulatus; C = D. leonhardi; D = D. simplex; E = D. matthewsi sp. n.; F = D. transcaspicus; G = D. vagabundus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669273/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
)............................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1904" box="[1291,1436,1301,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vagabundus">
<emphasis box="[1291,1436,1301,1323]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. vagabundus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" box="[151,1436,1331,1353]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1331,1353]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Protibiae wide, 3.25–3.6 times as long as wide (at widest level) (
<figureCitation box="[846,952,1331,1353]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,932,956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,908]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Dendarus spp., male protibia. A = D. armeniacus; B = D. crenulatus; C = D. leonhardi; D = D. simplex; E = D. matthewsi sp. n.; F = D. transcaspicus; G = D. vagabundus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669273/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 9A, E</figureCitation>
)...................................... 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
5 Protibiae with deep and wide notch on inner side and large acute tooth (
<figureCitation box="[907,984,1360,1382]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,932,956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,908]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Dendarus spp., male protibia. A = D. armeniacus; B = D. crenulatus; C = D. leonhardi; D = D. simplex; E = D. matthewsi sp. n.; F = D. transcaspicus; G = D. vagabundus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669273/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
); protibia much wider at level of this tooth than at apex; mesotarsi with 1 small brush on sole of tarsomere 2 (
<figureCitation box="[814,912,1389,1411]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,272,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-66@3.[151,1436,270,1664]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dendarus armeniacus, type specimens. A = Lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = type series; E = male mesotibia, ventrally; F = male mesotibia, laterally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669243/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 1E, F</figureCitation>
) or additionally with reduced tuft on sole of tarsomere 3; rarely mesotarsomeres without brush or tuft................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu G. Medvedev" authorityYear="1968" box="[1295,1436,1419,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armeniacus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1436,1419,1440]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. armeniacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,832,1500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Protibiae with small notch on inner side and small straight tooth (
<figureCitation box="[844,917,1448,1470]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,932,956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,908]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Dendarus spp., male protibia. A = D. armeniacus; B = D. crenulatus; C = D. leonhardi; D = D. simplex; E = D. matthewsi sp. n.; F = D. transcaspicus; G = D. vagabundus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669273/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 9E</figureCitation>
); protibiae slightly wider at level of tooth than at apex; mesotarsi with full brush on tarsomeres 2 and 3 (
<figureCitation box="[695,769,1477,1500]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669255/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
)...................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Nabozhenko &amp; Poggi, 2022" authorityName="Nabozhenko &amp; Poggi" authorityYear="2022" box="[1250,1376,1477,1499]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1250,1376,1477,1499]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. matthewsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1382,1436,1478,1499]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1382,1436,1478,1499]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
